    Deployed on Kubernetes
This deployment platform does not need Eureka server cos the service spring clouds provide is also on kubernetes.
Eureka server is a loadbalancer
In Kubernetes, there is a service that already provides the load balancing concept.
    Spring boot Microservices
    -Introduction to microservices Architecture
Microservices is architectural style where large applications are composed of small services
that provide specific business capabilities that can be deployed and managed independently.
    -Monoliths vs MicroServices - Pros & Cons
Monoliths architecture pros and cons
    pros                                    cons
Simpler development                         Difficult to scale sub-systems(modules)
Easier testing and debugging                Difficult to adopt new technologies
Simpler Deployment                          Higher chance to become big ball of mud
MicroServices architecture aka distributed computing solves all the problems of Monoliths architecture.
If you need a simple application, do not use distributed computing.
because every architecture comes with its own pros and cons
MicroServices pros and cons
    pros                                        Cons
can scale individual service                    Difficult to build & Manage distributed systems
smaller code bases                              Difficult to test & Debug
Easy to adopt new technologies if needed        Complex deployment process, performance issues

    Why rabitmq and not kafka
We use technology based off of the team strength.
Only one service is consuming our event, so our application doesn't need kafka like functionality.

    Spring cloud config
We use spring cloud modules to build micro services in spring boot.
One of them is spring cloud config
Instead of using application.properties, we can put all our application configuration in a central location(repository) and we can use spring cloud config modules.
So when we start the application, it will talk to the repository and fetch all the configuration.
    Service registry
Spring cloud supports Service registry like eureka, consul etc
The concept is we do not run one instance of a service in production, we run multiple instances.
If the client want to talk to any of the services, they will talk through the service registry(eureka server)
So if any of the service is down and the client calls a service, eureka server will automatically bring any one that is up.
    Kubernetes
This has a similar feature of the service registry.
In Kubernetes, each services run as a pod
If you run a service, Kubernetes will automatically serve as a load balancer.
since we are running on kubernetes, there's no reason to use a service registry.
    SDKMAN
This helps you install and switch between java versions

Todo 2
    create a catalog-service project with the following dependencies
Spring Web: for building restful apis
Validation: for bean validation
Spring Data JPA:
PostgreSQL Driver
Flyway Migration: for database migration
Spring Boot Actuator: for monitoring
Prometheus: for monitoring
Testcontainers: for testing
Spring Boot DevTools
Spring Configuration Processor

Add catalog service as a module to the root project
In TestcontainersConfiguration change the postgres from latest to 16-alpine

Run TestCatalogServiceApplication and do "docker ps" to see the postgres image running
then go to: http://localhost:8081/actuator, to see the actuator endpoints
then go to the application.yml in catalog-service to expose all the end points of actuator with "management:endpoints:web:exposure:include: *"
Add this two to catalog-service pom.xml "<goal>build-info</goal> & <plugin><groupId>pl.project13.maven</groupId><artifactId>git-commit-id-plugin</artifactId></plugin>"
In the sidebar, click maven and run the package folder to see git.properties
in the application.yml, add   Management:info:git: mode: full
then go to http://localhost:8081/actuator/info to see the git information in git.properties file
    Configure code formatting, swagger
go to https://springdoc.org/
For the integration between spring-boot and swagger-ui, add the library to the list of your project dependencies (No additional configuration is needed).
"   <dependency>
       <groupId>org.springdoc</groupId>
       <artifactId>springdoc-openapi-starter-webmvc-ui</artifactId>
       <version>2.8.17</version>
    </dependency>
"
